member.name: T:Microsoft.ML.Runtime.UniversalModelFormat.Onnx.Version
member.summary:
Versioning
ONNX versioning is specified in docs/IR.md and elaborated on in docs/Versioning.md
To be compatible with both proto2 and proto3, we will use a version number that is not defined by the default value but an explicit enum number.

member.name: F:Microsoft.ML.Runtime.UniversalModelFormat.Onnx.Version.StartVersion
member.summary: proto3 requires the first enum value to be zero. We add this just to appease the compiler.

member.name: F:Microsoft.ML.Runtime.UniversalModelFormat.Onnx.Version.IrVersion20171010
member.summary: The version field is always serialized and we will use it to store the version that the graph is generated from. This helps us set up version control. For the IR, we are using simple numbers starting with with 0x00000001, which was the version we published on Oct 10, 2017.

member.name: F:Microsoft.ML.Runtime.UniversalModelFormat.Onnx.Version.IrVersion20171030
member.summary: IR_VERSION 2 published on Oct 30, 2017 - Added type discriminator to AttributeProto to support proto3 users

member.name: F:Microsoft.ML.Runtime.UniversalModelFormat.Onnx.Version.IrVersion
member.summary: IR VERSION 3 published on Nov 3, 2017 - For operator versioning: - Added new message OperatorSetIdProto - Added opset_import in ModelProto - For vendor extensions, added domain in NodeProto

member.name: T:Microsoft.ML.Runtime.UniversalModelFormat.Onnx.AttributeProto
member.summary:
Attributes
A named attribute containing either singular float, integer, string, graph, and tensor values, or repeated float, integer, string, graph, and tensor values. An AttributeProto MUST contain the name field, and *only one* of the following content fields, effectively enforcing a C/C++ union equivalent.

member.name: P:Microsoft.ML.Runtime.UniversalModelFormat.Onnx.AttributeProto.Name
member.summary: The name field MUST be present for this version of the IR.

member.name: P:Microsoft.ML.Runtime.UniversalModelFormat.Onnx.AttributeProto.RefAttrName
member.summary: if ref_attr_name is not empty, ref_attr_name is the attribute name in parent function. In this case, this AttributeProto does not contain data, and it's a reference of attribute in parent scope. NOTE: This should ONLY be used in function (sub-graph). It's invalid to be used in main graph.

member.name: P:Microsoft.ML.Runtime.UniversalModelFormat.Onnx.AttributeProto.DocString
member.summary: A human-readable documentation for this attribute. Markdown is allowed.

member.name: P:Microsoft.ML.Runtime.UniversalModelFormat.Onnx.AttributeProto.Type
member.summary: The type field MUST be present for this version of the IR. For 0.0.1 versions of the IR, this field was not defined, and implementations needed to use has_field hueristics to determine which value field was in use. For IR_VERSION 0.0.2 or later, this field MUST be set and match the f|i|s|t|... field in use. This change was made to accomodate proto3 implementations.

member.name: P:Microsoft.ML.Runtime.UniversalModelFormat.Onnx.AttributeProto.F
member.summary: Exactly ONE of the following fields must be present for this version of the IR

member.name: T:Microsoft.ML.Runtime.UniversalModelFormat.Onnx.NodeProto
member.summary:
Nodes
Computation graphs are made up of a DAG of nodes, which represent what is commonly called a "layer" or "pipeline stage" in machine learning frameworks.
For example, it can be a node of type "Conv" that takes in an image, a filter tensor and a bias tensor, and produces the convolved output.

member.name: T:Microsoft.ML.Runtime.UniversalModelFormat.Onnx.ModelProto
member.summary:
Models
ModelProto is a top-level file/container format for bundling a ML model and associating its computation graph with metadata.
The semantics of the model are described by the associated GraphProto.

member.name: P:Microsoft.ML.Runtime.UniversalModelFormat.Onnx.ModelProto.IrVersion
member.summary: The version of the IR this model targets. See Version enum above. This field MUST be present.

member.name: P:Microsoft.ML.Runtime.UniversalModelFormat.Onnx.ModelProto.OpsetImport
member.summary:
The OperatorSets this model relies on. All ModelProtos MUST have at least one entry that specifies which version of the ONNX OperatorSet is being imported.
All nodes in the ModelProto's graph will bind against the operator with the same-domain/same-op_type operator with the HIGHEST version in the referenced operator sets.

member.name: P:Microsoft.ML.Runtime.UniversalModelFormat.Onnx.ModelProto.ProducerName
member.summary: The name of the framework or tool used to generate this model. This field SHOULD be present to indicate which implementation/tool/framework emitted the model.

member.name: P:Microsoft.ML.Runtime.UniversalModelFormat.Onnx.ModelProto.ProducerVersion
member.summary: The version of the framework or tool used to generate this model. This field SHOULD be present to indicate which implementation/tool/framework emitted the model.

member.name: P:Microsoft.ML.Runtime.UniversalModelFormat.Onnx.ModelProto.Domain
member.summary:
Domain name of the model. We use reverse domain names as name space indicators. For example: `com.facebook.fair` or `com.microsoft.cognitiveservices`
Together with `model_version` and GraphProto.name, this forms the unique identity of the graph.

member.summary: The version of the graph encoded. See Version enum below.

member.name: T:Microsoft.ML.Runtime.UniversalModelFormat.Onnx.GraphProto
member.summary:
Graphs
A graph defines the computational logic of a model and is comprised of a parameterized list of nodes that form a directed acyclic graph based on their inputs and outputs. This is the equivalent of the "network" or "graph" in many deep learning frameworks.

member.summary: A list of named tensor values, used to specify constant inputs of the graph. Each TensorProto entry must have a distinct name (within the list) that also appears in the input list.

member.name: P:Microsoft.ML.Runtime.UniversalModelFormat.Onnx.GraphProto.DocString
member.summary: A human-readable documentation for this graph. Markdown is allowed.

member.name: P:Microsoft.ML.Runtime.UniversalModelFormat.Onnx.GraphProto.Input
member.summary: The inputs and outputs of the graph.

member.name: P:Microsoft.ML.Runtime.UniversalModelFormat.Onnx.GraphProto.ValueInfo

member.name: P:Microsoft.ML.Runtime.UniversalModelFormat.Onnx.TensorProto.DataType
member.summary: The data type of the tensor.

member.name: P:Microsoft.ML.Runtime.UniversalModelFormat.Onnx.TensorProto.FloatData
member.summary: For float and complex64 values Complex64 tensors are encoded as a single array of floats, with the real components appearing in odd numbered positions, and the corresponding imaginary component apparing in the subsequent even numbered position. (e.g., [1.0 + 2.0i, 3.0 + 4.0i] is encoded as [1.0, 2.0 ,3.0 ,4.0] When this field is present, the data_type field MUST be FLOAT or COMPLEX64.

member.name: P:Microsoft.ML.Runtime.UniversalModelFormat.Onnx.TensorProto.Int32Data
member.summary: For int32, uint8, int8, uint16, int16, bool, and float16 values float16 values must be bit-wise converted to an uint16_t prior to writing to the buffer. When this field is present, the data_type field MUST be INT32, INT16, INT8, UINT16, INT8, BOOL, or FLOAT16

member.name: P:Microsoft.ML.Runtime.UniversalModelFormat.Onnx.TensorProto.StringData
member.summary: For strings. Each element of string_data is a UTF-8 encoded Unicode string. No trailing null, no leading BOM. The protobuf "string" scalar type is not used to match ML community conventions. When this field is present, the data_type field MUST be STRING

member.name: P:Microsoft.ML.Runtime.UniversalModelFormat.Onnx.TensorProto.Int64Data
member.summary: For int64. When this field is present, the data_type field MUST be INT64

member.name: P:Microsoft.ML.Runtime.UniversalModelFormat.Onnx.TensorProto.Name
member.summary: Optionally, a name for the tensor.

member.name: P:Microsoft.ML.Runtime.UniversalModelFormat.Onnx.TensorProto.DocString
member.summary: A human-readable documentation for this tensor. Markdown is allowed.

member.name: P:Microsoft.ML.Runtime.UniversalModelFormat.Onnx.TensorProto.RawData
member.summary:
Serializations can either use one of the fields above, or use this raw bytes field. The only exception is the string case, where one is required to store the content in the repeated bytes string_data field.
When this raw_data field is used to store tensor value, elements MUST be stored in as fixed-width, little-endian order. Floating-point data types MUST be stored in IEEE 754 format. Complex64 elements must be written as two consecutive FLOAT values, real component first. Complex128 elements must be written as two consecutive DOUBLE values, real component first. Boolean type MUST be written one byte per tensor element (00000001 for true, 00000000 for false).
Note: the advantage of specific field rather than the raw_data field is that in some cases (e.g. int data), protobuf does a better packing via variable length storage, and may lead to smaller binary footprint. When this field is present, the data_type field MUST NOT be STRING or UNDEFINED

member.name: P:Microsoft.ML.Runtime.UniversalModelFormat.Onnx.TensorProto.DoubleData
member.summary: For double Complex64 tensors are encoded as a single array of doubles, with the real components appearing in odd numbered positions, and the corresponding imaginary component apparing in the subsequent even numbered position. (e.g., [1.0 + 2.0i, 3.0 + 4.0i] is encoded as [1.0, 2.0 ,3.0 ,4.0] When this field is present, the data_type field MUST be DOUBLE or COMPLEX128

member.name: P:Microsoft.ML.Runtime.UniversalModelFormat.Onnx.TensorProto.Uint64Data
member.summary: For uint64 and uint32 values When this field is present, the data_type field MUST be UINT32 or UINT64
